in the labour market, the workers’ compensation system, the immigration process, and the legal system (both as litigants and as lawyers). It deepens our knowledge of the role of people with disabilities within social movements in disability history. The contributors encourage us to rethink our understanding of both the systemic barriers disabled people face and the capacity of disabled people to effect positive societal change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPeople with disabilitiesxGovernment policyzCanadaxHistory. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanadaxHistory. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxSocial conditions. 0aPeople with disabilitieszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aPeople with disabilitieszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aLAW / Disability.2bisacsh1 aBay, Odelia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolmage, Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinger, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaler, Dustin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsitt, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsitt, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeier, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalhotra, Ravi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalhotra, Ravi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPalmer, Bryan D., econ